  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2356082575" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2356082575" />
    <a title="Wendy S. Delmater" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12631365-wendy-s-delmater"><img alt="Wendy S. Delmater" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501693405p2/12631365.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2356082575?book_show_action=true">Apr 09, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Wendy S. Delmater" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Wendy S. Delmater" href="/user/show/12631365-wendy-s-delmater">Wendy S. Delmater</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2356082575" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer124087558939124886">Eminently readable and occasionally problematic, <i>The Dragonriders of Pern</i> trilogy is a classic in the science fiction genre that all serious students of science fiction should read, at least once. As much as I tell in this review I will not give away the main plot resolution, nor many of the fascinating subplots, but I will explore characters, so...mild spoilers ahead if you&apos;ve not read it yet <br/><br/>Book one of the trilogy starts in the point of view of a very strong female lead character, Lessa. She&apos;</span>
  <span id="freeText124087558939124886" style="display:none">Eminently readable and occasionally problematic, <i>The Dragonriders of Pern</i> trilogy is a classic in the science fiction genre that all serious students of science fiction should read, at least once. As much as I tell in this review I will not give away the main plot resolution, nor many of the fascinating subplots, but I will explore characters, so...mild spoilers ahead if you've not read it yet <br /><br />Book one of the trilogy starts in the point of view of a very strong female lead character, Lessa. She's the last surviving member of the noble family of Ruatha hold. The setting is reminiscent of a feudal one, except that she's obviously on another planet with different lifeforms, two moons, and a menacing Red Star. Every few hundred years this "star" spins a deadly silver rain of ravenous spores: their whole culture was set up to protect humans, dwellings, and crops from the spores, which they called Thread. The novel starts at the end of a 400-year period with no thread, and the ancient defenses against threadfall are in disrepair, the defenders in dishonor. Very few people think that thread will come again. Lessa is one of those who believes a thread-bearing "Pass" of the Red Star is nearly there, and feels it in her bones. <br /><br />But mainly, Lessa wants revenge and her heritage back ,and has worked long and hard in the shadows to make that happen. Lessa sees her chance when dragonrider F'lar comes to search for <br />a candidate for an about-to-be-hatched queen dragon egg. Suitable humans can telepathically bond with newborn dragons. In a section in F'lar's point of view Lessa causes F'lar, who also believes the Red Star is about to spin threads down on them, to duel with one of the chief disbelievers in thread. <br /><br />"Dragons" on Pern are cousins of a small indigenous lizard-like creature that have three useful characteristics. They can fly, chew a phosphorine-bearing rock to breath flame, and they can teleport, spending a brief time in a place people call "between." Dragonriders can therefore char thread out of the sky before it hits the ground. And they are almost extinct.<br /><br />Surprisingly, instead of ruling Ruatha, Lessa becomes the new queen dragon's mental and emotional mate: the last living queen dargon on Pern. When dragons<i> physically</i> mate, their humans get, shall we say, emotionally dragged into it. And the human of whichever dragon flies the queen becomes the new dragonweyr leader. F'lar's beast Mnemeth flies Lessa's queen dragon, Ramoth, and they become weyrmates, leading Pern's last surviving dragons and forcing an unbelieving and unprotected planet to prepare for the coming menace. <br /><br />The problematic part is that it is <i>casually mentioned</i> that F'lar continued the sexual relationship when the dragons were <i>not</i> involved, and in his own words it might as well have been called rape. In this day and age that's about as offensive as a minstrel show, or worse. Lessa eventually realizes how critical their role is in preparing the defenseless planet and supports F'lar, with their relationship evolving into a strong, mutually satisfying partnership, but their start is more than rocky. <br /><br />I'm not going to tell you how they--against all odds--manage to protect the planet, but it's ingenious and requires rare heroism on Lessa's part. <br /><br />In the second book, <i>Dragonquest</i>, the missing dragonweyrs have come back to fight thread, but are so out of touch with the rest of the planet that they cause all sorts of problems. These dragonriders cannot, will not, treat the "commoners" like anything other than subjects, and their arrogance is becoming intolerable. F'lar's half brother F'nor bears the brunt of this when he is attacked by one of the Oldtime dragonriders, who was trying to appropriate a jeweled belt-knife that was commissioned as a gift to a powerful Lord Holder. The Oldtime weyrleaders even try to wriggle out of their guilt about the knife attack. Masterharper Robinton, a very solid secondary character, brings F'lar reports of Oldtime weyrs even ignoring badly protected threadfalls and snatching women that interest them away from their families. <br /><br />Some of this book is from F'nor's perspective, and we see him recuperating from a serious knife injury in Southern Weyr, where the dragonriders have a sort of hospital. We meet Brekke, a shy young queenrider who is also a healer, and Kylara, a cast iron b*tch of a queenrider who's a vain, lazy maneater and whose nominal mate is the Werleader of Southern. Kylara is determined to seduce F'nor and becomes enraged when Brekke, who had a secret crush on F'nor, falls for him even though he rides the wrong color of dragon to fly her queen. F'nor rides a brown, and only bronze riders can fly queens. (We get more problematic sex here: Brekke wanted him yet fought him and F'nor forced her, but she really wanted it anyhow and...sigh. Somehow this, too, turns into a strong relationship eventually. Gawd.)<br /><br />F'lar ends up in a duel with the head of the oldtime weyrleaders when that guy finds out that one of his contemporaries let thread fall, unchecked, into a hold. F'lar barely defeats him but uses the fight to rally all the dragonriders around him, to protect the planet with honor. The lazy, rebellious oldtime dragonriders and their beasts are banished to Southern Weyr, and the folks from Southern are reassigned to the northern weyrs, the ones the rebellous oldtimers were ousted from. Brekke and Kylara end up too close to one of Kylara's paramours, and when Brekke's dragon makes its first mating flight, Kylara's dragon is too close and (stimulated by Kylara's appetites) rises to mate, too, and the queens fight. <br /><br />I'm not going to tell you what happens regarding drastic attempts to stop thread from <i>ever </i>falling on Pern again, but it involves F'nor and Brekke and every dragon on Pern. Slam-bang ending to the book, though. <br /><br />The final book in the trilogy--<i>The White Dragon</i>-- is mainly from the perspective of the child that Lessa, using a warder to raise him, put in charge of Ruatha Hold when she abdicated to become weyrwoman. Jaxom, now a young man, goes through the usual coming of age things, complicated by the fact that he's heir to a powerful hold, but not in charge, and that he inadvertently bonds with a hatchling sport dragon. <br /><br />(Note: more problematic sex here. Ruth is totally uninterested in mating, but being near mating dragons stirs desires in humans and Jaxom, who has a regular lover now, pretty much forces himself on her due to the desires stirred in him. At least he's embarrassed and ashamed afterward. But still.)<br /><br />The white dragon of the title, Ruth, is very small but we learn he's exceedingly clever. Ruth and Jaxon, denied training with the other werylings, because Jaxom must eventually become a Lord Holder, try to train on their own. This clandestine training leads them to thwart a plot by the banished oldtime dragonriders: they tried to steal a queen egg, and Ruth and Jaxom steal it back. During the cleanup after the heroic, secret act, Jaxom contracts a disease peculiar to Southerners. He fights thread with what he thinks is a head cold, and lays on a remote beach on the Southern continent to feel better. Ruth gets him medical help, because he nearly dies. <br /><br />Meanwhile, one of the oldtime weyrleaders, D'ram, tells Lessa and F'lar he wants to retire, for D'ram's weyrmate has died of a long illness and he's tired. He wants to throw the next mating flight of a queen in his weyr open to eligible bronzes and in that way choose a new weyrleader. But when the open mating flight happens, two of the rebellious bronze riders that had been banished to Southern show up, angry that their plot to get a queen egg failed, and suffering because there were no more living female dragons at Southern to give their males relief. <br /><br />One of the elderly dragons falters during the mating flight; the other dies and his rider goes insane and tries to kill F'lar. During the fight the beloved Masterharper, Robinton, has a heart attack. The grateful planet makes a place for Robinton to retire as an invalid - right where Jaxom is convalescing (and Jaxom has fallen for his healer, who becomes his wife and an important character in a later book). Much of the northerner's so-called gratitude is merely curiosity about the mostly-unexplored southern continent: things are getting crowded in the north. But F'lar wants the best part of the south so that dragonriders will not have to be beholden to the tithes of the holds, and can provide for themselves. <br /><br />It all culminates in Jaxom, under Robinton's direction, finding artifacts of the first interstellar settlers to Pern, 2500 years in their past. And these discoveries not only help the weryleaders know where to settle during the next interval. They also have the promise of getting much of their lost technology back<br /><br />Good series, worth reading. I'd give it 5 stars, but I took a star off the review for the problematic sex.</span>
  <a data-text-id="124087558939124886" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


